article.headline: Ford leads Shock with 17 points
article.linkText: Detroit overcomes 14-point deficit to beat Phoenix
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Detroit Shock didn't look like the best team
in the WNBA for much of the night.

But it did when it counted.

Despite trailing by as much as 14 points and committing 22
turnovers, the Shock took the lead in the final 3:33 and rallied
for a 78-76 victory over the last-place Phoenix Mercury (6-23) on
Wednesday night.

Cheryl Ford had 17 points and 15 rebounds, Deanna Nolan added 20
points and Swin Cash 19.

"Having 22 turnovers will not win games," said Ford, a Rookie
of the Year candidate.

Detroit averages a WNBA-worst 17.5 turnovers a game.

The Shock leads the Eastern Conference with a 21-8 record, but
the victory at American West Arena was its first in seven tries.

After Phoenix's Anna DeForge made a 3-pointer with 12.2 seconds
left to pull within 77-76, Nolan missed one of two free throws,
allowing Phoenix a last-second chance.

But DeForge missed a 21-footer with 2.5 seconds left and Detroit
ran out the clock.

Detroit (21-8) had to make up a 14-point deficit in the first
half and overcome 24 points scored by Phoenix off its turnovers.

"We started getting defensive stops," said Cash."I think
that's always the key; when you convert on the other end."

DeForge had 21 points, 12 on 3-pointers, to lead Phoenix. Adrian
Williams added 12 points and eight rebounds while Plenette Pierson
had 13 points off the bench for Phoenix.

Detroit trailed 37-32 at the half but needed to score the last
nine points of the half to get that close.

"It was a very unusual game," said Shock coach Bill Laimbeer.
"It had some of the dumbest turnovers we've ever seen."

He added, "We were fortunate to win the game. Our intensity in
the second half was much better than in the half. We just gave
ourselves the chance to win the game."

They did so by outshooting and outrebounding Phoenix (21-11) in
the second half.

After leading only in the first five minutes, Detroit didn't
regain the lead until Cash's layup with 7:18 to play in the game.

Despite trailing much of the night, the Shock got the lead for
good on Nolan's 3-point play with 3:33 left at 70-67.

Ford's free throws -- with 29.5 seconds left -- put Detroit up
76-71.

Plenette Pierson responded with 24.9 seconds remaining.

Nolan was fouled 1.2 seconds later and made one of two free
throws.

Detroit has a game and a-half on Western Conference leader
Houston (19-9) with five to play but already has home-court for the
first round of the playoffs.

The Mercury, last in the league in field goals, free throws and
total points and has lost three in a row.

The Shock leads the league in offense and rebounds.

"This was a big confidence booster for us," said DeForge, who
made 8 of 11 from the field. "We played well enough to win it and
all we needed was one or two more possessions."


^Notes: Detroit needs two wins or a win and a Charlotte loss to
clinch home court for the second round of the playoffs if they were
to make it that far. Half of Detroit's losses have come to the
Sting... The game was televised on NBA-TV, which is available on
digital cable systems and was the first WNBA game in history to be
televised in high-definition television... The Shock is now 3-9
against the Mercury.
